summary: Committed to ensuring 9/11 first responders and their families receive resources and health care for ongoing health challenges arising from their actions on that day. Also advocated protecting veterans' sensitive information at the VA by supporting the VA DATA Act to block DOGE from accessing veteran data and to restrict special government employees from extracting or retaining veteran data for non-governmental purposes. Additionally supported public-health-focused enforcement to curb illegal and unregulated e-cigarettes that threaten youth health and public safety. Stated readiness to negotiate with Republicans to keep government open and lower health care costs. Proposed and publicly defended amendments during House Veterans' Affairs Committee markup to protect veterans' access to Medicaid and nutrition assistance: an amendment to H.R.1336 to make veterans who lose Medicaid coverage between January 20, 2025 and January 19, 2029 eligible for VA Priority Group 6, and an amendment to H.R.980 to require the VA Secretary to provide a cash subsidy for nutrition assistance directly to veterans; both amendments were rejected by committee Republicans. Secured $847,000 for Deborah Heart and Lung Center Cardiac Electrophysiology Lab enhancements to upgrade hemodynamics systems and support advanced cardiac care locally. Cosponsored the Tobacco TRACE Act to reduce the prevalence of illegal and harmful tobacco products, lowering youth tobacco use and associated health care costs by improving regulators' ability to remove illicit products from the market. Recently announced his appointment to the House Veterans' Affairs Committee, stating he will use the position to more directly address veterans' health care, benefits, and family-support needs for the district's roughly 31,610 veterans. The announced senior staff includes Laney Oâ€™Shea, who led healthcare policy work for another Member of Congress, and Keith Roachford with long experience on veterans affairs, reinforcing the office's in-house expertise on healthcare and veterans issues. On February 4, 2025 he joined five other Democratic physician-members of the House in a public statement opposing the nomination of Robert F. Kennedy Jr. to be HHS Secretary, arguing the nominee promotes dangerous vaccine misinformation, would undermine science-based public health leadership, and could threaten access to basic mental and reproductive health services; the group urged the Senate to reject the nomination to protect evidence-based public health and community well-being. On March 14, 2025 he joined all six Democratic physician-Members in formally launching the Congressional Doctors Caucus, a caucus dedicated to promoting the health and well-being of Americans and advancing pragmatic, evidence-based health policy to lower costs, expand access, strengthen care delivery, defend vaccinations and public-health institutions, protect lifesaving research, and push back against medical misinformation and partisan attacks on science. Congressman Conaway is a physician with a medical degree and served as a Captain in the U.S. Air Force Medical Corps at McGuire Air Force Base; he also chaired the Health Committee during his 27 years in the New Jersey Legislature, and upon being sworn in he emphasized continuing to advocate on health and related family issues in Congress. The January 3, 2025 "Newest Members of Congress" release recorded his swearing-in and that commitment to continue advocating for health issues.

Gill introduced legislation to abolish the Fogarty International Center at NIH, arguing the center duplicates other NIH international research efforts (like NIAID), promotes 'global health equity' agendas he deems 'woke,' partners with the World Health Organization, and represents an unnecessary use of roughly $95 million in taxpayer funds; he framed its elimination as part of cutting wasteful federal health programs.

Supports extending Affordable Care Act premium tax credits via a clean, multi-year (three-year) extension to lower premiums and protect health coverage for working families; has joined colleagues in pressing House leadership to bring a clean extension to the floor and criticized members who opposed the vote. Cosponsored the Protecting Healthcare and Lowering Costs Act to restore ACA premium tax credits, and has backed broader health reforms including Medicare For All and other bills to restore and expand access to affordable healthcare and services for vulnerable populations.

Advocates enhanced medical and safety protections for professional boxers in H.R.4624, updating the Professional Boxing Safety Act of 1996 to improve medical standards and define national minimum health insurance requirements for fighters. The Muhammad Ali American Boxing Revival Act establishes a first-time national minimum of $25,000 in coverage for injuries sustained during a bout and includes supplemental provisions to improve boxer safety and well-being. The December 2025 press release highlighted broad stakeholder support including Mike Tyson and health and safety experts, and reiterated the mandatory health insurance provisions aimed at preventing fighters from having to choose between medical bills and careers.
